<font color="#FF0000">THE REAL FLAG DESECRATORS</font><br>
<tt>Mon May 19 11:27:24 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
It's important to consider that the proposed flag desecration amendment, if adopted, will only ban physical desecration of the flag.  It will have no effect upon those who by flying the flag over their despicable activities, desecrate what I was taught that the flag stands for.  <br><br>
For example, the CIA has been repeatedly guilty of flag desecration in its unscrupulous pursuit of our so-called &quot;national interests.&quot;  It has engineered the overthrow of democratically elected governments in Iran, Guatemala and Chile, to name but a few, and aided and abetted anti-democratic dictators in many other countries.  Most recently, a Handbook on Torture, published and distributed by the CIA in 1983 and for many years earlier to Central and South American military dictatorships, was finally brought to light.  <br><br>
For those of you disgusted by someone who burns a piece of cloth, please imagine how those of us who served 30 years ago allegedly in defense of democracy must feel realizing that they were part not of a defense of democracy but of an assault upon it, and all for the sake of American corporate interests.   The CIA is a flag-flying government agency, but they have desecrated the flag by turning it into a symbol of American state-sponsored terrorism...and no one questions their flag etiquette.<br><br>
Proper flag etiquette demands that soiled flags be burned. As VietNam veterans, we have the right and the duty to do just that when the government soils the flag in pursuit of its inhumane policies here or abroad.  The proposed flag desecration amendment does not protect the flag from its most disgusting and dangerous desecrators: those who would justify their criminal activities, and mute all criticism thereof, by wrapping them up in a deified piece of cloth.<br><br>
John M. Stassi<br>
Vets For Free Speech<br>
&quot;Free men can burn flags; slaves can only worship them.&quot;
